International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 8 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Hindu [edited]
<http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/holnus/002200411081465.htm>

Project to detect disease outbreak launched
---------------------------------------------
The Government today [8 Nov 2004] launched a mega-project aimed at
detecting disease outbreaks in the country well in advance. "The Integrated
Disease Surveillance Project (IDSP) launched today would help notify the
Center and state within 6 hours if a death occurs due to some disease, and
so detect disease outbreak well in advance," Union Health Minister Anbumani
Ramadoss told reporters here today. "It would help study the disease
patterns in the country and identify emerging diseases," he said.
The project, expected to provide essential data to monitor progress of
on-going disease control programs, would also help allocate health
resources more optimally, he added.
Under the project, each district of the country would have a well-equipped
lab with trained personnel and advanced communication facilities so that
they can send "early warning signals" to the higher authorities, he said.
"Initially, the project would be implemented in 9 states to test its
efficacy, and, by 2007, the whole country would be covered," the Minister
said. "Though the Project has 13 core priority areas for the national
surveillance, states could add some more according to their needs," Health
Secretary J.V.R. Prasada Rao said.
The 9 states to be covered include Andhra Pradesh, Himachal Pradesh,
Karnataka, Madhya Pradesh, Uttaranchal, Tamil Nadu, Mizoram, and Kerala and
cover a total of 206 districts in the 1st phase, he said.
--
